WEBVTT

00:02.440 --> 00:07.520
One of the things I always noticed in a department 
when I was running it, anytime you're talking

00:07.500 --> 00:14.640
about changes and suggestions from faculty, they 
pretend they're coming up with a big original idea

00:14.620 --> 00:19.520
about how to do graduate program or how to do this, 
how to do that. But when you investigate it in

00:20.020 --> 00:25.300
detail, you'll find that what they're proposing 
to do is exactly the same way they did it where they

00:25.280 --> 00:28.120
came from. And so I think anytime you get these 
outsiders coming in, you tend to, you do get some of

00:39.740 --> 00:42.260
that mixture, but I'm not sure it's always that 
great. Sometimes what we had was better than what

00:42.420 --> 00:45.280
they're trying to propose. I'll tell you one other 
thing that I've noticed that I think A&M ought to

00:47.440 --> 00:53.440
improve on. That is the way they treat their former 
presidents and so on. Now,

00:59.220 --> 01:08.230
when I came here, Walton had been president, and I 
think he was the one that got us that permanent

01:08.210 --> 01:10.330
fund, wasn't he? Well, we began to get a better 
share. I meant that was when he got, he was the one

01:14.770 --> 01:19.050
that looked up the law and got all that going. And he 
was running the post office or something. Then

01:24.640 --> 01:32.260
when Gilchrist stepped down, Fred Benson finally 
gave him an office over there in Zachary. Then when

01:33.440 --> 01:41.000
Benson finally stepped down, old Flipsy wouldn't 
even give him an office anywhere for a long time.

01:42.310 --> 01:48.730
And I just think that they lose a lot by not having 
these people more involved in. Now, I went to this

01:49.050 --> 01:54.510
little junior college, this little Baptist 
junior college, and we had, I think we had chapel

01:49.050 --> 01:54.510
every morning. And the guy that I took college 
algebra and trigonometry was born in about

01:55.310 --> 02:00.390
mid-1800s. Dr. R.L. Moore. Big, tall, skinny guy, 
wore a frock-tail coat and wing-tip collars with a

02:04.030 --> 02:10.090
string tie. And he didn't have any problem with 
what was right and wrong. But he was very revered.

02:18.800 --> 02:22.920
He sat up on the stage every day, and the president 
always deferred to him. And he was still teaching a

02:24.070 --> 02:29.670
course in college algebra and trigonometry, and 
he taught one in Greek. That was his, but he wanted

02:29.650 --> 02:34.560
to get associated with the average student. Not 
just the preachers. And every morning, I'll tell

02:36.800 --> 02:40.660
you this one, you might enjoy it. Every morning in 
class, he would tell us a little moral story. And it

02:47.240 --> 02:51.120
was also back in those depression days of 
encouraging students. Now, I don't know whether

02:51.200 --> 02:52.861
we do enough of that. Motivating them, just 
telling them, you've got to make something of

02:53.920 --> 02:56.860
yourself. And he mentioned that Dick Wayne, that 
Hall that used to be in mathematics, was in one of

02:58.580 --> 03:04.780
his classes. And he really worked hard. And he went 
on to be professor at one of the greater

03:06.460 --> 03:10.320
universities, is what he said. But he was, of 
course, against smoking and everything. He was so

03:17.070 --> 03:22.250
against smoking that what he did, they said at one 
time, was buy up all of the tobacco in the little

03:17.070 --> 03:22.250
town there, take it out on the middle of the campus, 
and burn it. But anyhow, in those years, and that

03:24.690 --> 03:35.170
was about 1939, the number one hit parade song was, 
I don't want to set the world on fire, I just want to

03:35.210 --> 03:39.010
start a flame in your heart. And old Dr. Moore came 
in one morning, and he said, and he always called us

03:39.730 --> 03:45.990
young people. He said, young people, I just don't 
know what this world's coming to. He said, I was

03:51.820 --> 03:56.920
coming to walk, walking to work this morning, and I 
passed this young man. He was pushing this

03:57.600 --> 04:03.800
wheelbarrow, and he was singing, I don't want to 
set the world on fire. And young people, he was. He

04:06.120 --> 04:07.073
wasn't. He wasn't. So, but I, now there is an 
example. We're not getting, I think there's a

04:13.690 --> 04:21.810
tendency in all organizations to let us just bury 
the guy once we get through with him. Instead of, if

04:23.150 --> 04:29.110
he was good enough to serve and run your 
organization, he would really be good enough to

04:23.150 --> 04:29.110
have around to help you. And we need to, that's one 
of the things that we need to take advantage of. I

04:34.950 --> 04:36.371
propose to. I propose to President Bowen, and I 
couldn't think of a better title than alumni

04:36.430 --> 04:44.170
professor. And I said, every year when the various 
faculty members retire, why not then try to look

04:44.530 --> 04:52.700
and say, which of these would we like to be able to 
still claim were part of our team, still use their

04:52.800 --> 05:00.980
talents and abilities, and ask the products of 
that department or that unit, would you help us?

05:09.060 --> 05:14.220
And I said, why not raise the money to give this 
person a small little honorarium so that this

05:15.890 --> 05:20.190
person could still teach a course or do a little 
research. We could call on for advice. Randy

05:23.570 --> 05:28.930
Mattson, then executive director of the former 
students, he said, I could raise that money with a

05:23.570 --> 05:28.930
few phone calls. But Dr. Bowen didn't see that as a 
good idea. I wonder how he will feel when he

05:32.410 --> 05:35.290
retires. Because see, just look what's happened 
to them. Mm-hmm. They're just walking around.

05:39.620 --> 05:40.235
Nobody. Yep. Yep. And Fred, old Flipsy, wouldn't 
even, and then Flipsy would just browbeat the hell

05:41.502 --> 05:50.530
