10:57.600 --> 11:04.140
realities of the College of Engineering, Texas 
Engineering Experiment Station, and the Texas

11:04.120 --> 11:09.714
Engineering Extension Service. Explain how 
those are related, and describe their functions.

11:15.465 --> 11:18.400
All right the Texas A&M, the College of 
Engineering is a part of Texas A&M University. The

11:24.897 --> 11:25.500
Texas Engineering Experiment Station is a 
separate state agency on a chart. It would occupy a

11:30.420 --> 11:35.400
position parallel to Texas A&M University, and 
also as I recall Texas Extension Service is the

11:35.380 --> 11:38.402
same way. And I'm not sure where the TTI is. as it may 
be where do they report they report they report now

11:41.242 --> 11:48.800
to the they well they've had them report in 
different ones they report now to the Dean Dean of

11:55.200 --> 11:59.400
Engineering because the Dean is in charge of all of 
it one time they reported to different people and

11:59.380 --> 12:02.640
there's where all the problem because the poor 
little faculty member he has to work for both of

12:02.620 --> 12:07.880
them all three of them and so all the problems come 
down and he's the stretch and you as a department

12:07.860 --> 12:14.820
head needed to be able I had to work with all of them 
yeah and you might want to get funding from all of

12:20.300 --> 12:25.520
them I'll tell you one another thing that I think 
that universities don't work nearly hard enough

12:25.500 --> 12:29.640
at in fact sometimes they go the wrong way well 
there are two things one of them just remind me if I

12:29.620 --> 12:33.960
don't come back to it is the coursework and another 
one is on funding funding people. The one on

12:42.100 --> 12:46.480
funding, all the time I was head of the department, 
I was able to keep everybody on a 12-month basis,

12:46.460 --> 12:52.839
regardless of whether they had research or not. 
And we did that by using gift and grant funds, and I

12:53.080 --> 13:00.040
just juggled it to where we made it work because 
it's very difficult to live on a nine-month

13:00.020 --> 13:03.903
salary. And so I felt like everybody that's around 
the university ought to be full-time employed.

13:09.739 --> 13:12.920
And I think that one of the things that stirs up more 
resentment on a university campus is having

13:12.900 --> 13:18.160
professors on a nine-month basis and 
administrators whom they are not really

13:18.140 --> 13:26.600
overenthusiastic

13:18.140 --> 13:26.600
about to begin with, any administrator, on a 
12-month basis. And here these people are trying

13:30.788 --> 13:32.600
to get by on a nine-month basis. And I think that 
what we ought to do is we've got a big, plant,

13:36.880 --> 13:42.029
millions of dollars invested in the facilities 
here. We ought to expand the summer program to

13:44.100 --> 13:47.269
where we've got 12-month employment throughout 
the year. We're not an agricultural society

13:48.500 --> 13:49.730
anymore. That was the reason that was originally 
set up. We ought to get around to the fact that we are

13:53.360 --> 13:58.151
a 12-month operation and that we need full-time 
employees. And I think you'd get a lot more loyalty

13:59.460 --> 14:05.200
among employees if you had because these can't get 
it and it's very difficult in some areas. It's very

14:06.880 --> 14:09.085
difficult in some areas to get research during the 
summer. And this shouldn't be the way we operate.

14:13.378 --> 14:17.080
And we should try to do it on a 12-month basis and 
have people doing something. There ought to be a,

14:17.847 --> 14:21.340
and I think there's a lot of students that want to 
take courses, more courses in the summer and can't

14:21.320 --> 14:24.540
get them because the money's not allocated for 
summer courses. They're trying, seem to be trying

14:26.456 --> 14:28.775
to keep those down. But they ought to be going the 
other way, is try to get more summer courses.

14:34.480 --> 14:36.081
Jumping way back. Yeah. Back now, as in those 23 
years that you were department head, looking

14:36.864 --> 14:45.120
back, who were some of the key faculty members that 
you brought in? I brought nearly the whole bunch. I

14:50.580 --> 14:53.860
know, but who were the ones that made the most, I'm 
not going to ask you the negative, just the

14:53.840 --> 14:54.861
positive. Well, actually most of them did all 
right. Who were the ones that were the cream of the

14:56.840 --> 14:59.600
crop? Well, Eubank was a good one. Who was? Harvey 
was a good one. Describe each one of them as you're

15:04.220 --> 15:05.241
going along. Okay. Okay. So, he came to us from Rose 
Poly as an undergraduate and went to, I've

15:07.220 --> 15:13.110
forgotten where he did go for his graduate work. He 
was in thermodynamics, and he helped get the

15:14.077 --> 15:18.650
thermodynamics program started. And he did, he 
was a good methodical teacher. He did teaching as

15:23.575 --> 15:26.410
well as research. And he's still involved. And 
then another one that I brought in was Ron Darby and

15:29.078 --> 15:36.320
he He wasn't as successful in getting research, he 
was probably more negative on putting in for it,

15:44.800 --> 15:55.670
saying he wouldn't get it or something like that, 
but he was a real good individual. So that was

15:55.650 --> 15:56.671
another one. Dick Davidson was another real good 
one that we brought in, and he had been good

15:56.650 --> 16:05.870
throughout his whole career. He was an excellent 
teacher, and original ideas, and good generally

16:06.850 --> 16:19.470
across the board.

16:19.450 --> 16:24.530
Let's see, Ray Anthony was another one, I brought 
him in. As you were recruiting these people, how

16:24.510 --> 16:31.090
did you identify the high quality faculty 
members, the potential faculty members, how did

16:31.070 --> 16:38.180
you find them? Oh. Well, some of these we checked to 
find out who was coming out of Rice. I knew the profs

16:45.540 --> 16:53.490
down there, the good ones, and I got some from them, 
and Ray, we'd had as a graduate student, went over

16:53.470 --> 17:01.000
to Texas, got his Ph.D., so we knew him.

17:00.980 --> 17:06.380
We also hired Hall in later, and although he's been 
through a lot of the things, I don't think he

17:06.360 --> 17:09.420
measures up to these other people. But he was, he's 
a really go-getter as far as hunting funds, but he

17:09.400 --> 17:15.500
doesn't have the staying power that I'd say some of 
the others did, as far as time after time. Let's

17:22.260 --> 17:30.960
see, I guess that, those are the old stand-bys that 
are over there. What were some, some kind of big

17:30.940 --> 17:41.940
step, big achievement research projects that the 
department did?

17:45.994 --> 17:53.380
Well, I think that the, they did, made numerous 
contributions in, in thermodynamics. They had a

17:53.360 --> 18:05.790
thermodynamics group that got together, and they 
all had several grants going there.

18:05.770 --> 18:09.930
And that carried on for a good long while to where 
it's gotten now very difficult to get that type of

18:09.910 --> 18:12.480
money. They want to put money on the ground. They 
want to put money on something that's going to be,

18:13.640 --> 18:18.910
turn the world around, you know. But this was 
collecting good, solid thermodynamic data that

18:18.890 --> 18:24.270
they did. Also in catalysis, there was quite a bit, 
we made a lot of progress in catalysis and

18:30.190 --> 18:30.715
kinetics. Ray Anthony and others worked on that. 
And Ron did some work on rheology. And I did a lot of

18:39.270 --> 18:41.350
work on distillation. In fact, I've got two 
papers. I'm trying to get out of the field, but I've

18:43.830 --> 18:47.030
got two papers right now that are going to be 
published. And one of them is going into a journal

18:47.655 --> 18:51.950
where one of the editors are retiring, and they 
asked me to write a paper. And I did, and I used a

18:53.930 --> 18:59.510
concept I've been using in teaching a class. And I 
wrote it up, and sure enough, it's accepted. It

19:03.720 --> 19:06.180
really wasn't any experimental research. It was 
just concept. It was ability, technique for

19:07.500 --> 19:13.840
representation of n-dimensional space. And not 
just three, four, five in two-dimensional space.

19:20.200 --> 19:23.980
And represent all the complexities there in two 
dimension. And it's real simple. It's very

19:24.960 --> 19:29.020
similar to just representing it for two 
components. And then another one that I've got

19:29.000 --> 19:35.790
coming out, I didn't really think about getting a 
paper. A guy from Vladivostok, a Russian, wrote me

19:36.294 --> 19:41.730
on email that he'd like me to send him some of the 
papers. That was a paper. That we had. And instead

19:45.710 --> 19:48.550
of doing that, what I did was just sit down and I 
said, well, that poor guy doesn't have any money,

19:48.530 --> 19:52.230
can't even buy the papers, and so on. What I'll do is 
just sit down and derive him some equations and

19:52.210 --> 19:56.890
give him ones that we haven't ever published 
before. And so I did. And he's ended up, he took

20:00.070 --> 20:04.750
those and made the problem a little bigger. And 
he's got a paper written now that I'm going to be a

20:04.730 --> 20:10.430
publisher with him. From Vladivostok. It's on the 
eastern front over there. Who

20:13.410 --> 20:24.050
were the big, were there any key industry 
supporters for chemical engineering research

20:24.030 --> 20:25.691
here during your years? Oh, yeah. We had Dow 
continue to support us some, and there weren't no

20:26.213 --> 20:33.310
real big ones, but enough grants. Dow, I got 
$20,000 a year to help me do this numerical stuff

20:34.234 --> 20:42.650
and theoretical developments, which was a good, 
back in those days, that's a good little sum of

20:42.630 --> 20:48.370
money just to have coming in every year. So we had 
some money like that. We had a lot. I also had some

20:52.690 --> 20:55.290
from the National Science Foundation. We got 
quite a bit that way, and other organizations.

20:59.310 --> 21:04.650
Also Amoco helped quite a bit with our labs and so 
forth. So we managed one way or another to get

21:04.630 --> 21:10.920
grants from one another and the government and all 
these people. So we had work done there. We had a

21:13.900 --> 21:15.361
great deal of management. We got to the center of 
it. A lot of our general leadership, our field

21:16.440 --> 21:18.860
management was under the leadership of the 
National Science Foundation. They were there for

21:20.840 --> 21:21.861
the board of directors. And that was going on. 
graduate students as well. Under your

21:25.840 --> 21:27.301
leadership, which do you think was more 
important? The theoretical or the practical

21:27.280 --> 21:29.440
research projects? Oh, I don't know that it was all 
that much. There really can't be divided that well

21:32.480 --> 21:38.280
down the line because there was a lot of 
theoretical concepts involved in a lot of them.

21:40.960 --> 21:43.500
There can be practical problems. And I don't know 
that I'd want to make a judgment on that. Of these

21:50.160 --> 21:54.420
key faculty, in your years of leadership, did we 
lose some key faculty members to industry or

21:54.400 --> 22:00.420
another institution? No, we really didn't lose 
many people.

22:07.110 --> 22:10.970
The only one, we lost one or two, but we weren't 
concerned about it because

22:10.950 --> 22:16.030
we weren't sure we wanted them anyway, and so they 
got hired somewhere else. We brought a whole group

22:18.870 --> 22:22.110
of young ones. Watson is another one that's done 
real well over there I didn't mention. But what we

22:25.950 --> 22:29.660
did was bring in these young ones, and we really 
rode hard on them to make sure they got started in

22:29.800 --> 22:35.120
research. How did you do that? Well, we met with 
them to find out what they were doing and giving

22:41.540 --> 22:44.500
them advice and also putting a little pressure on 
them. You want to try to write this proposal or that

22:44.520 --> 22:47.620
one? And so I think they thought we might have been a 
little hard on them, but there's the time to do

22:53.300 --> 22:56.780
something is when you first get them. And so they 
made it, and I got old Watson. Actually, I told

23:00.420 --> 23:04.420
Richardson this, and he was amazed that I did it. 
Watson came up for tenure, and the full professors

23:07.750 --> 23:11.470
looked at him and decided they didn't want to give 
him tenure. And so they reported me, and I said,

23:14.960 --> 23:18.080
well, I'm not really sure whether they know this 
man well enough. I'm going to see what. So I

23:19.540 --> 23:23.040
appointed another committee made up of the 
associate professors of his precise peers to make

23:23.020 --> 23:26.660
a judgment on him, what they thought about him. And 
they came up positive. And so I decided I'd go ahead

23:30.320 --> 23:33.220
and recommend him for tenure. And old Richardson 
says, you mean you went against your full

23:34.060 --> 23:37.780
professors? I said, well, I sure did, because I 
thought he deserved it. I don't know whether, I

23:41.160 --> 23:44.900
guess it could be debatable yet, but he's doing 
real well. Now, as an outsider, we heard a way over

23:46.740 --> 23:51.260
in history, I heard that it was common practice in 
engineering in those years that a new faculty

23:55.980 --> 23:59.380
member got a little bit of funding through the 
experiment station or some research account to

23:59.360 --> 24:03.320
start with. Yeah, we did some of that, and I gave 
them some department money. And that they were

24:05.900 --> 24:10.920
told that by the time three, four, five years in, in 
the future, they were expected to be getting their

24:10.900 --> 24:13.820
own research. Well, we tried to get them as soon as 
possible to start looking for it. Okay. Because it

24:19.046 --> 24:22.360
takes two or three years after you even start. So we 
had them start looking for it in some area that they

24:23.020 --> 24:26.780
were familiar with. And then we gave them enough 
to, tried to give them enough to get started trying

24:29.160 --> 24:32.760
to do something. Were there some individual 
honors that came to the department during your

24:36.540 --> 24:39.260
years of leadership that you'd like to? Well, I 
don't remember. All of them. We got nearly every

24:41.300 --> 24:45.220
one of them as these distinguished awards. Nearly 
everybody in the department got teaching or

24:45.360 --> 24:48.020
research. What about national or international 
awards? Yeah, there are several of those. As the

24:55.800 --> 25:00.560
years went on, with what other schools, by the time 
you retired as department head, what other

25:04.060 --> 25:09.020
schools should we be compared with in chemical 
engineering? Oh, I think that, University

25:11.160 --> 25:17.650
of Texas, Rice, all of these are strong schools. 
Were we in there? Well, we, I don't know that we're,

25:22.470 --> 25:25.690
University of Texas always had a little more 
support than we ever had. Boy, I'll tell you, we had

25:26.230 --> 25:29.530
so little support in the 50s. I remember Norman 
Road asked, they were building everything up at,

25:34.070 --> 25:36.750
what was the name of this school that went over to 
the university system? Arlington. They were

25:39.474 --> 25:41.660
building all kinds of engineering buildings up 
there. And we still had those old buildings over

25:41.760 --> 25:45.660
there where electrical was, you know. Back, I was 
in the Navy unit with Norman Road and Kenny Hancock

25:46.240 --> 25:52.260
and Fred Benson and Schiller. And Norman told us, 
he says, you know, I was talking to, I guess it was

25:58.240 --> 26:01.220
Mr. Gilchrist. I was talking to Mr. Gilchrist 
yesterday. I said, Mr. Gilchrist, you know how

26:02.760 --> 26:05.980
Norman was. He's very outspoken. You remember 
him, don't you? Norman Road. Are we getting ready

26:10.609 --> 26:11.460
to move? The college engineering up to Arlington?

26:15.860 --> 26:17.720
Mr. Gilchrist goes, I don't know why. He said, 
well, you're putting all the money in buildings up

26:17.780 --> 26:20.960
there instead of down here. But those were really 
lean years. I'll tell you, they really were. By

26:26.440 --> 26:29.060
comparison, what were the early 80s like? Well, 
where the change was was when we got Zachary. And

26:34.360 --> 26:37.140
that was about 73 or somewhere along there. And 
that, then we really were beginning to be, able to

26:41.700 --> 26:42.401
compete. Actually, when we had those old 
facilities, I didn't even like to take former

26:45.120 --> 26:48.600
graduate, I mean, potential graduate students 
through a lab because it was so ratty. In fact, when

26:53.100 --> 26:55.000
I had old Charlie over here, Jones that was 
president of Exxon, and Jim Galloway, I didn't

26:59.320 --> 27:01.840
realize they were as bad as they were. And I took 
them through, and we sat back down up there into my

27:03.040 --> 27:05.660
office, and old Charlie Jones says, Chuck, I'm 
clear you need some more facilities. And so an

27:11.600 --> 27:15.620
outsider could see it. And we didn't have, we got, 
we were on the list, and that used to worry Doc all

27:18.280 --> 27:20.300
the time, getting a new building. And I decided 
that's one thing I'm not going to worry about. It's

27:24.080 --> 27:25.541
more important what you do, regardless of what the 
dang building looks like, than having the

27:27.580 --> 27:29.001
building, because it's really the states anyway. 
But we were always first on the list, and then when

27:35.460 --> 27:36.281
we'd come along, Petroleum would get one. In fact, 
they got two before we ever got one. And, and, and,

27:41.420 --> 27:41.664
and, and, and, but finally we got in the loop and got 
some facilities, but we really didn't have that

27:47.130 --> 27:50.650
kind of support for a long time. And so we got behind 
and also not having girls over here. It was hard to

27:54.990 --> 27:58.630
draw graduate students in all those formative 
years, and so it wasn't an easy battle. As the years

28:01.030 --> 28:05.190
went on in the late 70s and 80s, did we begin to be 
competitive in salaries? Yeah, we're, we're

28:08.870 --> 28:11.430
closer to being competitive now. I think we 
probably are now. No, after they started kicking

28:13.990 --> 28:16.930
them up, we became, we were, started being 
competitive with salaries. I don't know exactly

28:20.850 --> 28:23.370
how they are. Some of these people watch them and 
plot them all the time. I don't, but I think our

28:25.530 --> 28:30.170
salary is pretty good right now. For you as a 
department head who also was a real world faculty

28:30.150 --> 28:35.170
member, what were the greatest joys of all these 
years? Well, I guess, actually, and it still is, is

28:41.410 --> 28:45.190
really getting up and teaching in class. 
Interaction with students and a lot of things I'm

28:45.170 --> 28:51.530
teaching, the courses I'm taught is I develop the 
books that I'm teaching out of and develop the

28:55.050 --> 28:57.550
theory that I'm teaching. So it's just a real 
pleasure to get up there and be able to explain

28:57.530 --> 29:04.370
things to students. I did, I taught a class this 
morning at eight o'clock. Please share if you can

29:07.770 --> 29:11.670
any examples of Aggie, good bull, tricks, pranks, 
that you may have been aware of. Surely, students

29:17.650 --> 29:24.040
must have tried to pull something on a chemical 
engineering faculty member somewhere along the

29:17.650 --> 29:24.040
line. Oh, well, I can tell you a couple that 
happened to faculty members, one of them. I had

29:30.400 --> 29:32.420
this graduate student, Nathan Welch, who was, I 
think he was hyperactive. And he, you'd see him

29:37.920 --> 29:41.510
walking up and down the hall. He was sharp as a tack. 
And, he'd have a Coke in one hand and a cigarette in

29:43.490 --> 29:48.720
the other and a pencil over his ear. And, just 
walking as fast as he could. And so one day I had to go

29:52.180 --> 29:56.480
out of town and I asked him to teach my class. And, I 
said, now, I want you to really give them a good

29:59.280 --> 30:03.300
presentation. And, he said, well, I'll give them 
one they'll never forget. So, when I got back, what

30:11.990 --> 30:13.011
had happened was, the students told me, that old 
Nate got in there, and he was just going like a house

30:15.990 --> 30:19.010
on fire. He was taking a swig of that Coke, and then 
he'd smoke a cigarette, and then he'd put the

30:21.990 --> 30:25.010
pencil up on his ear, and then he'd smoke a 
cigarette again. Finally, he laid the cigarette

30:26.990 --> 30:30.010
up on his ear. And, he says, don't you all tell Dr. 
Holland this, or this will be my last lecture.

30:43.050 --> 30:45.070
And then, old Dr. Lindsey, I remember one time, he 
was always huffing and puffing around. I was

30:48.050 --> 30:51.070
teaching a course over there in the new 
engineering building. He liked to go on

30:51.050 --> 30:54.070
inspection trips. We were getting ready to go on an 
inspection trip. And so, Doc was preparing them.

30:59.050 --> 31:01.070
And, he came over. And, he came blustering in 
there, and he told them about the trip.

